    <h1>Remediating Kubernetes Cluster using Kube-Bench tool</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p> Kube-bench is tool that checks whether Kubernetes is deployed s=
ecurely by running the checks documented in the <a href=3D"https://www.cise=
curity.org/benchmark/kubernetes/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">=
CIS Kubernetes Benchmark</a>. Once we have the scanning report we could be =
able to apply suggested fix to it referencing the steps documented in the C=
IS Kubernetes Benchmark available in the <a href=3D"https://downloads.cisec=
urity.org/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">CIS Benchmark download=
 page.</a> </p>
<h2 id=3D"RemediatingKubernetesClusterusingKube-Benchtool-Understandingtheo=
utputstatesinKubebench"><strong>Understanding the output states in Kube ben=
ch</strong></h2>
<p>When running kube-bench, you can get four output states:</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>PASS </strong>=E2=80=93 the test ran successfully and the re=
sults passed the standards.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>FAIL</strong> =E2=80=93 the test ran successfully and the re=
sults failed to meet the standards. You also receive a remediation output, =
which either describes how you can fix the configuration, or provides an er=
ror message that explains why it was not possible to run the test.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>WARN </strong>=E2=80=93 the test requires further attention.=
 A remediation output provides specific information regarding the matter.</=
p></li>
<li><p>I<strong>NFO</strong> =E2=80=93 provides informational output that d=
oes not require any further action.</p></li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"RemediatingKubernetesClusterusingKube-Benchtool-ApplyingRemediati=
on/FixinaccordancetoCISKubernetesBenchmark"><strong>Applying Remediation/Fi=
x in accordance to CIS Kubernetes Benchmark</strong></h2>
<p>Download the <strong>CIS Kubernetes Benchmark</strong> PDF from the <a h=
ref=3D"https://downloads.cisecurity.org/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"no=
follow">CIS Benchmark download page.</a> The manual will be referred to as =
a guide for remediating issues. To track a =E2=80=98<strong>fail</strong>=
=E2=80=99 in the kube bench test, get the ID and search for it in the manua=
l.</p>
<p><strong>NOTE: When referring to CIS Kubernetes Benchmark ensure that you=
 have the specific PDF for your platform, depending if you working on the D=
IY Cluster (Self managed cluster) or the GKE Cluster.</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><p>CIS Kubernetes Benchmark v1.6.0</p></li>
<li><p>CIS Google Kubernetes Engine (GKE) Benchmark v1.1.0</p></li>
</ul>
<p></p>
<p>Here are steps to follow to track a =E2=80=98<strong>fail</strong>=E2=80=
=99 in the kube bench test:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Download the specific CIS Benchmark for your cluster.</p></li>
<li><p>Get the ID and search for it in the manual.</p></li>
<li><p>As an example, let say we had a fail in our DIY cluster after runnin=
g the kube bench test with the description below: </p></li>
</ul>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro confluence-information-macro-inf=
ormation">
<span class=3D"aui-icon aui-icon-small aui-iconfont-info confluence-informa=
tion-macro-icon"></span>
<div class=3D"confluence-information-macro-body">
<p>'[FAIL] 4.2.6 Ensure that the --protect-kernel-defaults argument is set =
to true (Automated)'</p>
</div>
</div>
<ul>
<li><p>We will note the ID as <strong>4.2.6</strong> and search for its rem=
ediation in the CIS Kubernetes Benchmark v1.6.0.</p></li>
<li><p>Then follow the remediation and Apply the fix.</p></li>
</ul>
    </div>
